In [17]:

a=np.array(data[data['Personal Loan']==0].Age)
b=np.array(data[data['Personal Loan']==1].Age)
t_stat, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(a,b,axis=0)
print("the caluclated value of tstatistic is",t_stat)
print("The pvalue is",p_value)
print(""*1000)
print("Based on the statistical evidence")
if p_value > 0.05:
    print("we fail to reject null hypothesis as the p_value", p_value, "is greater than 0.05")
    print(null)
else:
    print("we reject null hypothesis as the p_value", p_value, "is less than 0.05")
    print(alternate)

the caluclated value of tstatistic is 0.5461906615539323
The pvalue is 0.584959263705325

Based on the statistical evidence
we fail to reject null hypothesis as the p_value 0.584959263705325 is greater than 0.05

KNN¶

  • This model gave best results because in grid search, as we got k=1, and when k is small it tends to overfit capturing both the information as well as noise
  • The same happened even after upsampling

Logistic Regression¶

  • Since, most of the data attributes are normally distributed, Logistic regression gave a decent accuracy.
  • Data normalization is also an other reason.

Naive Bayes¶

  • If there would have been more possibilities among the data, Naive bayes would perform even better.
  • When upsampled, there will be repitions of data which does not increase the possibilities and hence Naive bayes failed after upsampling of the data.

SVM¶

  • This ML algorithm gave the best results.
  • Even though there is only a slight improvement in test accuracy from 98.13 to 98.48, before sampling results are significant because it has less number of false positive and false negative

Here, SVM tend not to overfit and hence SVM is the best model¶
